[{"sha":"212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Fix state migration remote version check

Previously the state migration process was using the fallback strict
error check when migrating to or from a Terraform Cloud workspace. This
resulted in an error when running init if the local and remote Terraform
versions did not exactly match.

This was excessively strict. When migrating from a remote Terraform
Cloud workspace to local state, there is no need for a version check at
all, as we cannot break the Terraform Cloud workspace. When migrating
to Terraform Cloud, we should use the more forgiving check, rather than
the strict equality.

This commit fixes both of these cases accordingly, and allows migrating
state to and from Terraform Cloud remote workspaces without errors.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818"},{"sha":"44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove InitProvisioner and close all at once

InitProvisioner only stored the provisioner in the cache and provided a
way to return an error. We can push this back further into the cli init
process, but for now we can move the error into the Provisioner call and
drop InitProvisioner.

This also changes CloseProvisioner to CloseProvisioners, in preparation
for the removal of the graph nodes.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68"},{"sha":"a6db207b8772cc874723b4d8100c9e19a51a8a3e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove provisioner graph nodes

Provisioners are always run via a single instance, and their
configuration and references are taken care of via their parent
resource, so there is no need to maintain the provisioner graph nodes.

The only action that will still need to be completed is calling the
Close method for external plugins. This was not consistently done with
the current handling of provisioners anyway, and we can now add that to
a single point with the new CloseProvisioners context method.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/a6db207b8772cc874723b4d8100c9e19a51a8a3e"},{"sha":"fe7635f438c15458a88f95fdb80c0874c93f8f36","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"always close all provisioners after each walk


Change-Id: I4afa0b7d657fedf2ef5355e5065eb82b8a7f4b74","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/473d70ed4ee455b41bbbc74f71bf094411bcf783"},{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

[{"sha":"492aba6feb5048ec717d725a35a073355b35dbce","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update xtensa fully_connected kernel to call into xa_nnlib.

This is the relevant code snippet from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.

[{"sha":"9a2150719b971adf078eca5cecbb18c146545cbd","author":{"name":"Sebastian Silbermann","email":"84fc128bc6cda84e77606b9e3bddd28c2b9ce031@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix prod build in ci/codesandbox (#20606)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rishi93/react/commits/9a2150719b971adf078eca5cecbb18c146545cbd"},{"sha":"af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update DevTools to use getCacheForType API (#20548)

DevTools was built with a fork of an early idea for how Suspense cache might work. This idea is incompatible with newer APIs like `useTransition` which unfortunately prevented me from making certain UX improvements. This PR swaps out the primary usage of this cache (there are a few) in favor of the newer `unstable_getCacheForType` and `unstable_useCacheRefresh` APIs. We can go back and update the others in follow up PRs.

### Messaging changes

I've refactored the way the frontend loads component props/state/etc to hopefully make it better match the Suspense+cache model. Doing this gave up some of the small optimizations I'd added but hopefully the actual performance impact of that is minor and the overall ergonomic improvements of working with the cache API make this worth it.

The backend no longer remembers inspected paths. Instead, the frontend sends them every time and the backend sends a response with those paths. I've also added a new "force" parameter that the frontend can use to tell the backend to send a response even if the component hasn't rendered since the last time it asked. (This is used to get data for newly inspected paths.)

_Initial inspection..._
```
front |                                                      | back
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:true) ---------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes with no updates..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:false) --------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (no-change) -- |
```
_User clicks to expand a path, aka hydrate..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:true) ----> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes during which there is an update..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:false) ---> |
      | <----------------- "inspectedElement" (full-data) -- |
```

### Clear errors/warnings transition
Previously this meant there would be a delay after clicking the "clear" button. The UX after this change is much improved.

### Hydrating paths transition
I also added a transition to hydration (expanding "dehyrated" paths).

### Better error boundaries
I also added a lower-level error boundary in case the new suspense operation ever failed. It provides a better "retry" mechanism (select a new element) so DevTools doesn't become entirely useful. Here I'm intentionally causing an error every time I select an element.

### Improved snapshot tests
I also migrated several of the existing snapshot tests to use inline snapshots and added a new serializer for dehydrated props. Inline snapshots are easier to verify and maintain and the new serializer means dehydrated props will be formatted in a way that makes sense rather than being empty (in external snapshots) or super verbose (default inline snapshot format).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rishi93/react/commits/af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe"},{"sha":"ba9582da27481677cdac2dd000a438147a5df88e","author":{"name":"ChenLei","email":"2078e632128f17c4aa4e413d134a36c7418bccff@qq.com"},"message":"[devtools] Fix can't expand prop value in some scenario (#20534)

[{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

[{"sha":"492aba6feb5048ec717d725a35a073355b35dbce","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update xtensa fully_connected kernel to call into xa_nnlib.

This is the relevant code snippet from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```

Change-Id: I4afa0b7d657fedf2ef5355e5065eb82b8a7f4b74","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/473d70ed4ee455b41bbbc74f71bf094411bcf783"},{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

[{"sha":"492aba6feb5048ec717d725a35a073355b35dbce","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update xtensa fully_connected kernel to call into xa_nnlib.

This is the relevant code snippet from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```

[{"sha":"a5d5542434120f390f6add73102db674eb400539","author":{"name":"mergify[bot]","email":"b09a6ee808b67e98a221404e7aaa52e0398a4954@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"fix(kumactl) de-duplicate passed env-vars (#1367) (#1443)

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

Change-Id: I82622536fd89ce77993bcfe1c65f5f172e8ebcd4","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/37d51318b0680d99970790ccd1bb42454acbf2bb"},{"sha":"ea46ce224f29eea984ca04c6362b2d36d039565c","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Fix //tensorflow/core/common_runtime/eager:custom_device_test on Windows

The test on Windows needs an extra dependency on variable ops. Without an explicit dependency it seems like the ops themselves aren't registered, but based on logged errors the kernels try to register anyway.

It shouldn't be possible to get kernels without ops. This could be related to the is_external flag on tf_gen_op_lib which affects Windows linking. But it's a bit more complicated than I can figure out by trial and error on an extremely long presubmit.

Signed-off-by: Charly Molter <charly@koyeb.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/004a4e14350941b158b04c12fb29c2f1a210856f"},{"sha":"de170f1b889d0562321bced10097edfcbba147ce","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"6d801fb2355a07c9e004ea4635b4ce3edfe405d7@koyeb.com"},"message":"fix(dns) allow resolution of service names with "." (#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

This is the relevant code snippet from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```

[{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more
context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209"}]

[{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

[{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

[{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

This is the relevant code snippet from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```

Signed-off-by: Charly Molter <charly@koyeb.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/004a4e14350941b158b04c12fb29c2f1a210856f"},{"sha":"de170f1b889d0562321bced10097edfcbba147ce","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"6d801fb2355a07c9e004ea4635b4ce3edfe405d7@koyeb.com"},"message":"fix(dns) allow resolution of service names with "." (#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

[{"sha":"492aba6feb5048ec717d725a35a073355b35dbce","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update xtensa fully_connected kernel to call into xa_nnlib.

This is the relevant code snippet from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

[{"sha":"44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove InitProvisioner and close all at once

InitProvisioner only stored the provisioner in the cache and provided a
way to return an error. We can push this back further into the cli init
process, but for now we can move the error into the Provisioner call and
drop InitProvisioner.

This also changes CloseProvisioner to CloseProvisioners, in preparation
for the removal of the graph nodes.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68"},{"sha":"a6db207b8772cc874723b4d8100c9e19a51a8a3e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove provisioner graph nodes

Provisioners are always run via a single instance, and their
configuration and references are taken care of via their parent
resource, so there is no need to maintain the provisioner graph nodes.

The only action that will still need to be completed is calling the
Close method for external plugins. This was not consistently done with
the current handling of provisioners anyway, and we can now add that to
a single point with the new CloseProvisioners context method.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/a6db207b8772cc874723b4d8100c9e19a51a8a3e"},{"sha":"fe7635f438c15458a88f95fdb80c0874c93f8f36","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"always close all provisioners after each walk

This was not done consistently in all cases when the individual
provisioner graph nodes were used. Since we removed the graph nodes, the

[{"sha":"212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Fix state migration remote version check

Previously the state migration process was using the fallback strict
error check when migrating to or from a Terraform Cloud workspace. This
resulted in an error when running init if the local and remote Terraform
versions did not exactly match.

This was excessively strict. When migrating from a remote Terraform
Cloud workspace to local state, there is no need for a version check at
all, as we cannot break the Terraform Cloud workspace. When migrating
to Terraform Cloud, we should use the more forgiving check, rather than
the strict equality.

This commit fixes both of these cases accordingly, and allows migrating
state to and from Terraform Cloud remote workspaces without errors.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818"},{"sha":"36f44331ad4b142ed771d55d7a2eb12042a43242","author":{"name":"The Terraform Team","email":"2a56ea1490dced68c01a1ee616138a226895907a@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge 212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818 into backport/alisdair/remote-backend-version-check-state-migration/hopelessly-capable-stud","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/36f44331ad4b142ed771d55d7a2eb12042a43242"}]

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```

The previous logic assumed that all mhlo.dot is at most R2 but that isn't
the case. This change reuses the mhlo.dot_general legalisation code to
handle all possible mhlo.dot operations and to also reduce code duplication.

The newly generated (and more complex) patterns are already simplified away
by subsequent passes.

[{"sha":"492aba6feb5048ec717d725a35a073355b35dbce","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update xtensa fully_connected kernel to call into xa_nnlib.

This is the relevant code snippet from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581 that is needed to
use xa_nnlib with the fully_connected kernel for fusion_f1.

Profiling the keyword benchmark shows a reduction of ~20000 ticks for
invoke (if we use the updated xa_nnlib from
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/44581)

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 279792 ticks (279 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 151304 ticks (151 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1512547 ticks (1512 ms)
```

Also confirmed that the kernel_fully_connected_test passes:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_fully_connected_test -j8
```
